elements.content: Two three-dimensional interpenetrating coordination polymers, [Co(C8H4O4)(C12H10N2)] n , 1, and [Zn3(C14H8O4)3 (C12H10N2)2] n , 2, have been prepared hydrothermally by the assembly of cobalt(II), 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene (C12H10N2) with terephthalic acid (C8H4O4), and zinc(II), 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene with biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylic acid (C14H8O4), respectively. Single-crystal X-ray diffraction analyses reveal that 1 and 2 have similar 2-fold interpenetration. Because of the influence of metal ions, the O,O‘-donor ligands adopt similar coordination modes but form different kinds of individual motifs, which finally aggregate to generate different supramolecular architectures. The structures of the two three-dimensional interpenetrating open frameworks have been characterized and studied.

elements.content: Reaction of cobalt surface heptahydrate with 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene and terephthalic acid, zinc chloride with 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene and biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylic acid, respectively, by a hydrothermal method afforded two closely related three-dimensional coordination polymers. Both structures show interpenetrating cubes but the node is completely different.

elements.content: In recent years, the use of crystal engineering concepts has produced a variety of coordination networks, many of which exhibit unusual and fascinating modes of entanglement of individual motifs. Among different types of net-assembled molecular frameworks reported so far, interpenetrating networks are of particular interest concerning the topological types of three-dimensional (3D) nets postulated by Wells. The design and self-assembly of interpenetrated networks, in which molecules are entangled, is an important activity in supramolecular chemistry, for both aesthetic and utilitarian reasons. A typical interpenetrating polymer network (IPN) is composed of two or more independent polymer networks with the same or different chemical compositions. In IPNs, all components have overlapping three-dimensional structures within the same spatial volume and penetrate into each other without chemical bonds between them.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

In recent years, the use of crystal engineering concepts has produced a variety of coordination networks, many of which exhibit unusual and fascinating modes of entanglement of individual motifs. Among different types of net-assembled molecular frameworks reported so far, interpenetrating networks are of particular interest concerning the topological types of three-dimensional (3D) nets postulated by Wells. The design and self-assembly of interpenetrated networks, in which molecules are entangled, is an important activity in supramolecular chemistry, for both aesthetic and utilitarian reasons. A typical interpenetrating polymer network (IPN) is composed of two or more independent polymer networks with the same or different chemical compositions. In IPNs, all components have overlapping three-dimensional structures within the same spatial volume and penetrate into each other without chemical bonds between them.

elements.content: There is an increasing interest in these species not only for their potential properties as functional solid materials, in host−guest chemistry, ion exchange, catalysis, and for the development of optical, magnetic, and electronic devices, but also for their intriguing architectures and topologies. Synthetic approaches making use of carefully selected, suitable metal centers as nodes and exo-bidentate or multifunctional ligands as connectors have produced numerous fascinating archetypal structures, including diamond (66-α), α-Po (41263), α-ThSi2 (103-b), SrSi2 (103-a), PtS (4284), SiO2 (6482-b), and NbO (6482-a), the theory-predicted topologies of which were all experimentally confirmed. These inorganic/organic frameworks often contain large open spaces that may be subject to interpenetration. All of these extraordinary structures are of fundamental importance in structural design and in the understanding of structure−property correlations.

elements.content: We are particularly interested in self-assembly of different kinds of coordination open frameworks; the aim of our investigation is to obtain coordination polymers with interpenetrating networks, possibly showing new modes of entanglements. Here, we report two interpenetrating three-dimensional open frameworks, [Co(C8H4O4)(C12H10N2)] n , 1, and [Zn3(C14H8O4)3(C12H10N2)2] n , 2. In the two coordination open frameworks, because of the influence of metal ions, the O,O‘-donor ligands adopt similar coordination modes but form different kinds of individual motifs, which finally aggregate to generate different supramolecular architectures. But these two different structures show similar interpenetration modes.

elements.content: In the design and self-assembly of interpenetrating networks, a large number of molecular building blocks have been employed, suitable, at least in principle, for the assembly of desired structures. Among them, different types of ligands, with rigid or flexible backbones and variated donor functionalities, have been used together with metal centers, resulting in the formation of interesting structural motifs. It is well-known that product topology can often be controlled and modulated by selecting the coordination geometry of the metal ions and the chemical nature of the organic ligands. Usually, long ligands will lead to larger voids that may result in interpenetrated structures, the most outstanding example of which is 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane. With this ligand, many beautiful interpenetrated networks of ingenious design have been constructed, ranging from interpenetrating 1D ladders to 3D nets.
elements.clean_text:
Results and Discussion

In the design and self-assembly of interpenetrating networks, a large number of molecular building blocks have been employed, suitable, at least in principle, for the assembly of desired structures. Among them, different types of ligands, with rigid or flexible backbones and variated donor functionalities, have been used together with metal centers, resulting in the formation of interesting structural motifs. It is well-known that product topology can often be controlled and modulated by selecting the coordination geometry of the metal ions and the chemical nature of the organic ligands. Usually, long ligands will lead to larger voids that may result in interpenetrated structures, the most outstanding example of which is 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane. With this ligand, many beautiful interpenetrated networks of ingenious design have been constructed, ranging from interpenetrating 1D ladders to 3D nets.

elements.content: Benzenedicarboxylate ligands and their derivatives have been extensively employed to link metal ions to produce high-dimensional frameworks containing channels or cavities. On the other hand, flexible dipyridyl ligands with certain spacers, such as 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)-ethane, 1,2-di(4-pyridyl)ethylene, and 1,3-bi(4-pyridyl)propane, can freely rotate to meet the requirement of coordination geometries of metal ions in the assembly process. These ligands are good candidates for producing unique structural motifs with beautiful aesthetics and useful functional properties. The combination of dicarboxylate and dipyridyl ligands with metal ions has resulted in various supramolecular complexes with different structures and functions. For example, Fu et al. have obtained an interpenetrated network reacting terephthalic acid with 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane and cobalt ion. In this paper, terephthalic acid, biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylic acid, and 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene were chosen as starting organic ligands. Our purpose was to investigate whether similar ligands could obtain similar interpenetrating networks. These two organic acids react with 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene and cobalt/zinc ions under the same conditions. Finally, an interpenetrating network similar to that in ref was obtained when terephthalate anion and 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene coordinated to the cobalt cation, but when biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate anion and 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene coordinated to the zinc cation, a novel interpenetrating network was obtained. Because of the influence of the metal ion, the two similar O-donors accept similar coordination modes (Scheme ), but finally result in different coordination open frameworks.

elements.content: Crystal Structures. From Figure , we can see that the cobalt center has a distorted octahedral coordination geometry, with two oxygen donors of one chelating bis-bidentate carboxylate group and two oxygen donors of two bridging bidentate carboxylate groups in the horizontal direction. The coordination sphere is completed by two nitrogen donors of 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene in the axial direction. This coordination mode in compound 1 generates a parallelepiped individual motif. This structure is similar to that in ref , but because of the flexibility of 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane, the individual motif of ref is cuboid. Each corner of the parallelepiped is occupied by a binuclear subunit and the Co···Co separation in the binuclear subunit is 4.12 Å, which is shorter than that of 4.27 Å in reference. Eight terephthalate ligands form the length and width of the parallelepiped, whereas eight 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene ligands make up the height of it. The aggregation of the parallelepiped individual motif results in a 3D framework, and the 3D networks interlock with each other to display a 2-fold interpenetrating mode. As shown in Figure , in the axial direction, every two rods (rod aa and bb) in the parallelepiped are associated with one particular quadrate ring (ring 1) of the other framework through which they pass, whereas in the horizontal direction, one rod (rod cc) is associated with two particular quadrate rings (ring 2 and 3) of the other framework through which it penetrates; this interpenetration mode is also the same as that in ref . Each binuclear subunit in the framework acts as a six-connected node by connecting the four carboxylate groups from the terephthalate ions at the equatorial positions to form a 2D Co-terephthalate (4,4) network and by further bonding to the nitrogen atoms of the 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene ligands to give rise to a unique network with a 4646 topology. A 2-fold interpenetrating framework is generated by incorporating two identical 4646 networks into the structure. As clearly illustrated in Figure , pure six-connected binuclear subunits constitute the nodes of this structure.

elements.content: For the preparation of compound 2, the biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate ligand was used instead of the terephthalate ligand. Zn1 metal has a distorted octahedral coordination. The apical positions are occupied by two nitrogen atoms (N2C and N2D) from two 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene ligands, whereas the equatorial positions are occupied by four oxygen atoms (O4, O5, O4B, and O5B) from four different carboxylate groups of four different biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate anions. But the Zn2 atom has a distorted tetrahedral coordination geometry, being coordinated by one N atom (N1) of a 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene molecule and three oxygen atoms (O2, O3, and O6) from three different carboxylate groups of three different biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate anions, which provide the four connecting nodes that result in an unsymmetrical adamantane-type unit. The distortions of the unit can arise from the application of different ligands. Zn1 and Zn2 are connected by two bridging bis-bidentate biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate bianions, and there is also a symmetrical Zn2B cation on the other side of Zn1. The three Zinc cations (Zn2−Zn1−Zn2B) are connected by biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate bianions, forming a symmetrical trinuclear subunit; Zn1 lies on a special position of 1̄ site symmetry (Figure ). The coordination mode in compound 2 generates a novel parallelepiped individual motif. Each corner of the parallelepiped is occupied by a trinuclear subunit, and the Zn···Zn separation in the trinuclear subunit is 4.13 Å. Twelve biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate ligands form the length and width of the parallelepiped block, whereas eight 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene ligands make up the height of it. The aggregation of the parallelepiped individual motif results in a 3D framework, and the 3D networks interlock with each other to display a 2-fold interpenetrating mode. As shown in Figure , there are also particular quadrate rings of the other framework in compound 2, just like that in compound 1. Each trinuclear subunit in the framework acts as a six-connected node by connecting the six carboxylate groups from the biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate ions at the equatorial positions to form a 2D Zn−biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylate (4,4) network and by further bonding to the nitrogen atoms of the 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene ligands to give rise to a novel network with a 4646 topology. A 2-fold interpenetrating framework is generated by incorporating two identical 4646 networks into the structure. As clearly illustrated in Figure , pure six-connected trinuclear subunits constitute the nodes of this structure.

elements.content: Using similar ligands 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene instead of 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane, we obtained the structure, compound 1, that is similar to that in ref . Compounds 1 and 2 have similar ligands and similar coordination modes; the only difference in these two compounds is that the metal ions are slightly different, which results in completely different node and exhibition of different structural motifs. The difference in central atoms makes the metal ion accept different coordination geometry and leads to different open framework modes. Thereby, the metal ion is an essential factor in controlling the subunits of 1 and 2. From Figures and , we can see that the parallelepiped blocks in the open framework of compound 1 are highly ordered, whereas the parallelepiped blocks in the open framework of compound 2 are highly distorted because of the different coordination geometry of the zinc cation. It is very interesting to note that 1 and 2 exhibit similar interpenetration modes, despite their having different kinds of open frameworks. What is the reason for the phenomena? Let us look again at the coordination environments of the metal ions in 1 and 2. In 1, the Co atom has a distorted octahedral coordination geometry, whereas in 2, the zinc1 atom has a distorted octahedral coordination geometry and the zinc2 atom has a distorted tetrahedral coordination geometry. However, despite this distinct disparity, the ligands around the metal ions in 1 and 2 are similar; the coordination modes of these ligands are also similar. These similar ligands and coordination modes may be the reason for the similar interpenetration behaviors.

elements.content: IR Spectroscopy. The IR spectrum of compound 1 shows characteristic bands of the dicarboxylate groups of terephthalate ligands at 1628 and 1565 cm-1 for asymmetric vibrations and at 1474 and 1401 cm-1 for symmetric vibrations. The Δ values, which represent the separation between νasym(−COO) and νsym(−COO), are 154 and 164 cm-1, respectively. For compound 2, the characteristic bands of the dicarboxylate groups of biphenyl-4,4‘- dicarboxylate ligands are shown at 1681 and 1605 cm-1 for the asymmetric vibrations and at 1418 and 1294 cm-1 for the symmetric vibrations. The Δ values are 263 and 311 cm-1, respectively. The splitting of νasym(−COO) in compounds 1 and 2 confirms that the carboxylate groups have two different coordination modes, which is in agreement with their crystal structures. The absence of the expected characteristic bands at 1730−1690 cm-1 for the protonated carboxylate groups indicates the complete deprotonation of terephthalic acid and biphenyl-4,4‘- dicarboxylic acid in the reaction with Co and Zn ions.

elements.clean_text:
Conclusion

The hydrothermal reactions of cobalt sulfate heptahydrate with terephthalic acid and 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene, zinc chloride with 1,2-bis(4- pyridyl)ethene and biphenyl- 4,4‘-dicarboxylic acid, respectively, produced two different interpenetrating networks.

elements.content: Similar ligands and similar coordination modes result in similar 2-fold interpenetrating behaviors. But different metal ions result in different individual motifs, which induce different supramolecular architectures. In summary, this research reveals that organic ligands and metal ions both play an important role in constructing interpenetrating networks; spacer ligands and their coordination modes control the interpenetrating modes, and metal ions can modulate connection fashions and individual motifs. To design and construct desired structures, one should not only choose proper ligands, but also select proper metal ions as nodes to connect organic ligands.

elements.content: Materials and General Methods. Terephthalic acid, 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene, and biphenyl-4,4‘- dicarboxylic acid were purchased from Fluka and used without further purification; all the other reagents were commercially available and used as purchased. IR spectra (KBr disk) were recorded on an EQUINOX55 (Bruker) spectrophotometer. Carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen were determined using an EA 1112 elemental analyzer. Single-crystal reflection data were recorded on a Bruker Smart-1000 CCD diffractometer.
elements.clean_text:
Experimental Section

 Materials and General Methods. Terephthalic acid, 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethene, and biphenyl-4,4‘- dicarboxylic acid were purchased from Fluka and used without further purification; all the other reagents were commercially available and used as purchased. IR spectra (KBr disk) were recorded on an EQUINOX55 (Bruker) spectrophotometer. Carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen were determined using an EA 1112 elemental analyzer. Single-crystal reflection data were recorded on a Bruker Smart-1000 CCD diffractometer.

elements.content: X-ray Crystallographic Studies. Intensity data for 1 and 2 were measured on a Bruker Smart 1000 CCD diffractometer with graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) at room temperature. All empirical absorption corrections were applied by using the SADABS program. The structures for 1 and 2 were solved by direct methods and refined on F 2 by full-matrix least squares using the SHELXL-97 program package. The positions of hydrogen atoms were generated theoretically (C−H bond fixed at 0.93 Å), assigned isotropic thermal parameters, and allowed to ride on their parent carbon atoms before the final cycle of refinement. Crystal data and structure determination summary for 1and 2 are summarized in Table . The selected bond lengths and bond angles for 1 and 2 are listed in Tables and , respectively.
